<br>
Noise and confusion.  The world is spinning around me, or am I spinning?  The ground is far below, yet I am not falling.  Fear, terrible fear, and hatred.  My hatred?  Plant, dirt, debris, fly around me, as if a tornado is ripping through the lands.  I try and run from it.  There is a house nearby, I can seek shelter in there.  Run towards the house, must escape.  As I arrive, the house is ripped to shreds.  I turn around and to horror see that the destructive winds have followed me.  I look down and the occupants of the house are running away screaming.  The destructive force has followed me.<br>
<br>
No, I am the tornado.  I have destroyed this quiet home, torn these kind people from their house.  What have I done?  I run off away from the house, plants, dirt and debris flinging aside where I run.  Those whom I have sought help from I have only hurt.  All that I touch is destroyed.  A terrible knot forms in my gut as I think about what I have done.  I can not help but crumple over myself and weep.  I am not a hurricane, I don’t destroy houses!  Do I?<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> I was glad when I was out of Kithicor onto the trail to the pass.  I was even more glad when I found the keep and was able to stop for a real meal, since I had skipped breaking my fast to get out of the forest as soon as the dread eased at dawn.  The guard at the pass is heavy, but I needed food.  I managed to find an unwary traveler and lightened their purse.  I think a guard saw me, but if they did, they did nothing.  Better fed, I was sure to depart immediately.<br>
<br>
Crossing the planes of Karana is always quite a task.  I only made it about half way before the sun was threatening to dip behind the mountains.  Clouds were rolling in from the east, and a small storm ensued.  Drenched, I plodded on, looking for some shelter.</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
The winds faded and gave way to a light rain over the lands.  The patter of drops around me unknots my stomach and I am able to regain myself.  All around me there is destruction.  My destruction.  I hate myself for what I have done.  Someone puts a reassuring hand on my shoulder.<br>
<br>
Behind me, the old elf comforts me, though his expression is one of anger.  Anger directed at someone else, not at me.  I start to confess that I caused the destruction, but he stops me before I start.  The rain comes down harder, yet we do not get wet.  A curtain of water hides the destruction from me.  I protest, I do not want to be shielded from what I have done.  The elf just continues to comfort me.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Shelter found me quickly.  A farmer shouted out to me nearby.  He asked if I had anywhere to stay the night and keep out of the rain.  I said no, and he offered me shelter and bed.  Not one to turn down the offer, I accept and follow him into his house.  He sits me down and gives me a small meal and sits me in front of the fire to eat.  I ate while he just waited quietly.  When I finished eating I thanked him for the shelter and meal.  I may be opportunistic, but I am still grateful for help.<br>
<br>
He told me that it came to him in a vision from Karana that I would be coming.  He doesn’t know who I am, or why I come, but he could not leave me out in the rain.  He told me of Karana, or the rainkeeper as some know him.  The rain is a blessing of Karana, he told me.  Karana is wise, bringing rain for the crops, and kind, for he stays his hand at the full fury of the storm.  A religious nut, but at least it is out of the rain.</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
The curtain of rain fades and all around me I see the rain has brought new life out of the destruction I caused.  The sorrow and heat in my heart is replaced by joy and celebration.  How can I fear and hate with all this glory around me.  I turn to embrace the old elf, but he is nowhere to be seen.<br>
<br>
Off in the distance there is a city, standing in glory, defying the destruction that came before.  A crow flaps by overhead, flying towards the city.  I chase after the crow, but it is faster than me.  It caws three times, then continues out of sight towards the city.  A sweet aroma comes from the city.  Or is it from the city?  I wake up to the scent of the farmer preparing a meal to break his fast.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> I take a last bite of the morning meal the farmer offered me.  I have not had such a nice meal in a long time.  I will have to come repay this farmer his kindness some time.  Still, maybe I should listen to his rant.  All my dreams are about rain and storms.  Perhaps the old elf is not my father, but is Karana.  Could it too be a vision from the rainkeeper?  If so, to what purpose do I travel west?  Perhaps I should share my dream with him and see if he has any idea what it means.<br>
<br>
What am I thinking, he’s a nut, plain and simple.  But I cannot deny the calling I feel to travel west.  I cannot explain it, yet it is there.  Once I get to Erudin, I hope someone there can tell me what is happening.</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
