<br>
Clockwork.  I'm in Ak'anon.  I went to Ak'anon.  This must be the work of another crazy gnome's clockwork.  No, I think I remember now.</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
The road leading up to Ak'anon is twisty and can sometimes be dangerous, but I have almost arrived.  However, the steamfont mountains are somewhat quiet, in a disturbing way.  I round a hill and the entrance to Ak'anon is visible over the hells.  I start running through in my head the demands to make of the gnomes for the crazy tinkerer with the clockwork spider.<br>
<br>
Something is amiss.  There are normally guards posted at the entrance, yet none are now present.  Probably for the better, whatever their reason it just makes it easier for me.  I stroll in and try to remember the directions around the city I was given.  Lost in thought, I round a corner with less care than I should have, just in time to hear a scream.  Snapping out of my wandering thoughts, I duck into a shadow and freeze.  There is clanging of weapons and armor ahead.  Some battle commences forth, yet I do not know why.<br>
<br>
Skillfully I slink through the shadows into the city.  There I see the most horrid sight; gnomes slaughtered by the dozens, their clockwork in pieces among the bodies.  But not just gnomes, other races too.  This is clearly a city under attack, and with many allies here to defend the city.  Some evil force moves in here.  I have no love for gnomes, but the sight is disturbing.  These people live here, their very home is being invaded, giving them nowhere to turn to should they be run out.  My mission now completely forgotten, I must press on and find out more.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  I roll over and try to prop myself up on my hands, but a sharp pain in my left arm quickly ends that effort.  With a grunt I collapse back down onto the ground in pain.  Someone who was leaning over another limp figure turns at the sound and leans over me.  A female elf, pureblood it looks like.  She tells me, &quot;Relax, just lie there.  It is safe now, we will take care of you.&quot;  Her gentle touch and soothing voice calm me more than her words.  My head continues to throb with pain however.  The elf turns away and leaves my line of sight.  I decide I do not have the energy to turn and see where she went at the moment.</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
Carefuly to avoid detection, I sneak past the battle.  The further I go in, the more bodies I see, littering the halls and chambers of the city in the mountain of steam.  Slipping along the underside of a bridge over water, I make my way towards a central looking structure.  If my sources are correct, this should be the throne room.  Making my way swiftly and quietly inside, avoiding the bodies of the falled gnomes, I find the head of the offensive force.  There the king himself, and his guards, are battling to hold off what the rest of the city could not.  Dark elves battled the gnomes and the clockworks.  The king appears to be winning, but I feel uneasy, so withdraw as one of the dark elves falls.<br>
<br>
Back out the way I came, the shouts of triumph behind me warming my heart a little.  As I make my way back out of the chambers of the king, the sound of battle once again reaches my ears, and the sharp calls of the Iksar along with it.  Racing in the direction the sound comes from, I stop short of the door and peer in, carefully working to remain hidden.  Inside, a few of the force of attackers stands in defiance of all that would challenge them.  Repeatedly brave fighters approach, and repeatedly they fall.  As I watch in horror, defender after defender falls.<br>
<br>
I try my best to remain firm, but a tear creeps into my eye.  Past memories long forgotten are re-awoken.  There was a couple of humans I once called parents.  They lived in the slums of the city of Freeport.  They were not my real parents, but they treated me like they were.  That all came crashing down the day the so called militia raided our homes and slayed the humans, all in the name of justice and peace.  But peace is exactly what they robbed from me.<br>
<br>
And justice is what I shall now seek!  The memory sparked a fire, which now rages inside me.  This iksar here may not be the militia who robbed those that I cared about from me, but they are no better.  I don't care what it takes, I will step in and stop it.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  I close my eyes and start to fall asleep again, but a human male approaches me.  I make a motion to stop and protect myself, but he just stops and waits for me to calm down.  He speaks to me, &quot;Don't move, I am here to help.&quot;  His voice is rough, but his actions are as kind as the elfs.  Muttering a few words, a blue glow emanates from his hands and surrounds him and me.  I can feel my body being mended from the inside.  Cuts closing up, wounds healing over, and bones knitting themselves back together.  There is a brief sharp pain, then the human stops and the glow fades.  He tells me, &quot;Just rest for a bit, you will still be quite sore.&quot;  I start to protest, but he is gone before I get a chance.</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
The burning desire consumed me, and shocked by my own boldness I step out into the open.  Raising my voice above the clamor of battle, I declare, &quot;This is not my battle, nor do I particularly care for these gnomes.  But this bloodbath must be stopped.&quot;<br>
<br>
The Iksar turns to face me and raises his weapons.  His blade swings, and faster than I knew I could, I dodge.  I cease to think, and just react.  But the lizard is fast, and catches me with his blade on a stroke back.  Before I even have time to feel the pain, I am dazed by a blow to my body, then another right after.  I barely manage to dodge a kick and make an attempt to duck out of sight, so I can sneak in for a chance to bury my pick into his back.<br>
<br>
I have never seen anybody move so fast.  My attempt to duck out of sight fail horridly, and another blow knocks me off my feet.  I try to scramble back, but am met yet again by a blade carving deeply into my flesh as if I were wearing no armor at all.  Another blow and I am again dazed.  The iksar calls out in a rough accent, &quot;Now YOU die, Mithlin!&quot;  I completely panic and again try to find somewhere to hide, but a blade finds its mark in my arm.  Again and again I am pounded by the merciless beating.  I throw in all my effort to swinging my pick at the lizard, trying to fend off the next blow, but my hastily aimed swing goes wide, leaving my side exposed.  The iksar takes the oppertunity presented him and his blade meets my flesh.<br>
<br>
Everything goes dark.  The sounds of battle continue, as if off in the distance, in some dream.  It was all a dream, and now I rest.<br>
<br>
And nothing.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  What a fool have I been.  I thought I would be the one to save these people from my fate.  But if anything I have just learned how little training I have.  And what little intellegence, too.  For if these healers were not here, surely I would not have a second chance.<br>
<br>
But I have a second chance.  I have a second chance at life, and a second chance to right what has gone wrong in the world.  I have been reborn anew, with a will I knew not I had.  What is the point of living if there is no point to life?  Not just my life, but all life.  I have been becoming leanred in the skills of battle, but my abilities are but a whisper of the storm they will be.<br>
<br>
No more will I sit idle while the world falls into destruction.  No more will I not see beyond my own well being.  This is not about a single crazy gnome, this is much bigger.  Forgetting all aches, I leap up and call out, &quot;Listen to the whisper now because the storm comes!  I am the storm!  I am Lussarrna!&quot;</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> <p>Mithlin Lussarrna<BR>
